  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. These include:\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):** This convention was one of the first international agreements to specifically address money laundering, focusing on proceeds derived from drug trafficking.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** While not a treaty, the FATF is an inter-governmental body that sets international standards to combat money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. It issues recommendations that are widely adopted by countries around the world.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000):** This convention covers money laundering related to a broader range of crimes beyond drug trafficking, including organized crime.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003):** This convention also addresses money laundering as it relates to corruption offenses.\n\nThese laws and conventions require signatory countries to criminalize money laundering, establish regulatory frameworks for financial institutions to detect and prevent money laundering, and cooperate with other countries in investigating and prosecuting money laundering offenses.",
